<document>
<title>List of NBA champions</title>
<fragment>

The current home-and-away format in the NBA Finals is 22111 (the team with the better regular-season record plays on its home court in Games 1, 2, 5, and 7), which has been used in 19471948,[5] 19501952,[6][7][8] 19571970, 19721974, 19761977, 19791984, and 2014present. It was previously in a 232 format (the team with the better regular season record plays on its home court in Games 1, 2, 6, and 7) during 1949, 19531955, and 19852013,[9][10] in a 1111111 format during 1956 and 1971,[11][12] and in a 12211 format during 1975 and 1978.[13][14]


As of 2023[update], the Eastern champions have a 4037 advantage in NBA titles over the Western champions, with their most recent being the Milwaukee Bucks in 2021.[15][*bettersourceneeded*] The Boston Celtics and the Minneapolis/Los Angeles Lakers have won a combined total of 34 NBA championships, with 17 apiece in their rivalry.[16] As of 2023[update], the defending champions are the Denver Nuggets.

<fragment>

The current home-and-away format in the NBA Finals is 22111 (the team with the better regular-season record plays on its home court in Games 1, 2, 5, and 7), which has been used in 19471948,[5] 19501952,[6][7][8] 19571970, 19721974, 19761977, 19791984, and 2014present. It was previously in a 232 format (the team with the better regular season record plays on its home court in Games 1, 2, 6, and 7) during 1949, 19531955, and 19852013,[9][10] in a 1111111 format during 1956 and 1971,[11][12] and in a 12211 format during 1975 and 1978.[13][14]


As of 2023[update], the Eastern champions have a 4037 advantage in NBA titles over the Western champions, with their most recent being the Milwaukee Bucks in 2021.[15][*bettersourceneeded*] The Boston Celtics and the Minneapolis/Los Angeles Lakers have won a combined total of 34 NBA championships, with 17 apiece in their rivalry.[16] As of 2023[update], the defending champions are the Denver Nuggets.
